      "index": "b90",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1324422096,
      "version": 65,
      "versionNonce": 1245384656,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1779821148912,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Cache Stampede (Thundering Herd): Cache stampede (or thundering herd) occurs when a popular cache key expires, causing \nhundreds of concurrent requests to simultaneously hit the backend database. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Cache Stampede (Thundering Herd): Cache stampede (or thundering herd) occurs when a popular cache key expires, causing \nhundreds of concurrent requests to simultaneously hit the backend database. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "nrAg4a0uMD_3gJuuXirWL",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 568.98828125,
      "y": 2590.5859375,
      "width": 1299.4388427734375,
      "height": 425,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b91",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1671586608,
      "version": 132,
      "versionNonce": 488690480,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1779821530324,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Solutions:\n(i) Request Coalescing (Singleflight) This is the most common solution. When a cache miss occurs, the first request acquires a \nlock (distributed or in-process) and begins fetching data from the backend. Subsequent requests for the same key \ndetect the lock and wait for the result rather than triggering new queries. Once the first request completes, \nthe cache is populated, and waiting requests retrieve the fresh data. \n\n(ii) Probabilistic Early Expiration Instead of waiting for a key to expire, this approach (such as the XFetch algorithm)\n randomly refreshes cache entries before their TTL ends. The probability of refreshing increases as the expiration time approaches. \nThis statistically spreads out the load over time, preventing a sudden surge of requests when a key expires. \n\n(iii) Stale-While-Revalidate When a cache key expires, the system returns the stale cached data immediately\n to the user while triggering a background refresh. This ensures low latency for users and prevents the backend \nfrom being overwhelmed, as the expensive fetch operation happens asynchronously after the response is served. \n\n(iv) Distributed Locking In distributed systems (e.g., using Redis), a distributed lock prevents multiple servers from \nfetching the same data simultaneously. If a lock is acquired, the server fetches and caches the data; if not, other\n servers either wait briefly or return a cached stale value. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Solutions:\n(i) Request Coalescing (Singleflight) This is the most common solution. When a cache miss occurs, the first request acquires a \nlock (distributed or in-process) and begins fetching data from the backend. Subsequent requests for the same key \ndetect the lock and wait for the result rather than triggering new queries. Once the first request completes, \nthe cache is populated, and waiting requests retrieve the fresh data. \n\n(ii) Probabilistic Early Expiration Instead of waiting for a key to expire, this approach (such as the XFetch algorithm)\n randomly refreshes cache entries before their TTL ends. The probability of refreshing increases as the expiration time approaches. \nThis statistically spreads out the load over time, preventing a sudden surge of requests when a key expires. \n\n(iii) Stale-While-Revalidate When a cache key expires, the system returns the stale cached data immediately\n to the user while triggering a background refresh. This ensures low latency for users and prevents the backend \nfrom being overwhelmed, as the expensive fetch operation happens asynchronously after the response is served. \n\n(iv) Distributed Locking In distributed systems (e.g., using Redis), a distributed lock prevents multiple servers from \nfetching the same data simultaneously. If a lock is acquired, the server fetches and caches the data; if not, other\n servers either wait briefly or return a cached stale value. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
